<subSubSection pageId="4" pageNumber="579" type="diagnosis">
<paragraph blockId="4.[151,1437,845,1673]" pageId="4" pageNumber="579">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[199,314,1193,1220]" pageId="4" pageNumber="579">Diagnosis</emphasis>
. Forewing length is 17–17.5 mm in males (
<quantity box="[794,872,1194,1221]" metricMagnitude="-2" metricUnit="m" metricValue="1.7" pageId="4" pageNumber="579" unit="mm" value="17.0">17 mm</quantity>
in the 
<typeStatus box="[945,1045,1194,1221]" pageId="4" pageNumber="579">holotype</typeStatus>
) and 
<quantity box="[1104,1182,1194,1221]" metricMagnitude="-2" metricUnit="m" metricValue="1.9" pageId="4" pageNumber="579" unit="mm" value="19.0">19 mm</quantity>
in females. Externally, the new species (
<figureCitation box="[341,441,1229,1256]" captionStart="FIGURES 1–8" captionStartId="3.[151,264,1968,1993]" captionTargetBox="[223,1383,309,1933]" captionTargetId="figure@3.[190,1397,306,1941]" captionTargetPageId="3" captionText="FIGURES 1–8. Ghoria spp., adults. Depositories of specimens: 1–4, 6–8 – MWM/ZSM; 5 – SZMN (photo by V.V. Dubatolov)." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.3887622" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/3887622/files/figure.png" pageId="4" pageNumber="579">Figs 6–8</figureCitation>
) can be easily distinguished from other relatives with whitish hindwing including female of 
<taxonomicName authority="Volynkin &amp; Saldaitis &amp; Černý, 2020" authorityName="Volynkin &amp; Saldaitis &amp; Černý" authorityYear="2020" box="[180,303,1264,1290]" class="Insecta" family="Arctiidae" genus="Ghoria" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Lepidoptera" pageId="4" pageNumber="579" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="mubupa" status="sp. n.">
<emphasis box="[180,303,1264,1290]" italics="true" pageId="4" pageNumber="579">G. mubupa</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
<emphasis bold="true" box="[309,372,1264,1290]" pageId="4" pageNumber="579">
<taxonomicNameLabel box="[309,372,1264,1290]" pageId="4" pageNumber="579" rank="species">sp. n.</taxonomicNameLabel>
</emphasis>
by its brownish grey frons and orange collar (both are yellow in other species). The male genital capsule of 
<taxonomicName authority="Volynkin &amp; Saldaitis &amp; Černý, 2020" authorityName="Volynkin &amp; Saldaitis &amp; Černý" authorityYear="2020" box="[276,439,1298,1325]" class="Insecta" family="Arctiidae" genus="Ghoria" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Lepidoptera" pageId="4" pageNumber="579" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="longivesica" status="sp. n.">
<emphasis box="[276,439,1298,1325]" italics="true" pageId="4" pageNumber="579">G. longivesica</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
<emphasis bold="true" box="[447,513,1298,1324]" pageId="4" pageNumber="579">
<taxonomicNameLabel box="[447,513,1298,1324]" pageId="4" pageNumber="579" rank="species">sp. n.</taxonomicNameLabel>
</emphasis>
(
<figureCitation box="[528,659,1298,1324]" captionStart="FIGURES 20–23" captionStartId="8.[151,264,1884,1909]" captionTargetBox="[155,1435,185,1854]" captionTargetId="figure@8.[151,1435,181,1858]" captionTargetPageId="8" captionText="FIGURES 20–23. Ghoria spp., male genitalia. Specimens are deposited in MWM/ZSM." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.3887628" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/3887628/files/figure.png" pageId="4" pageNumber="579">Figs 22, 23</figureCitation>
) is similar to that of 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Dubatolov, Kishida &amp; Wang" authorityYear="2012" box="[903,1058,1298,1325]" class="Insecta" family="Arctiidae" genus="Ghoria" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Lepidoptera" pageId="4" pageNumber="579" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="nanlingica">
<emphasis box="[903,1058,1298,1325]" italics="true" pageId="4" pageNumber="579">G. nanlingica</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
(
<figureCitation box="[1075,1204,1298,1324]" captionStart="FIGURES 17–19" captionStartId="6.[151,264,1697,1722]" captionTargetBox="[197,1385,168,1682]" captionTargetId="figure@6.[189,1398,166,1687]" captionTargetPageId="6" captionText="FIGURES 17–19. Ghoria nanlingica sspp., male genitalia. Depositories of specimens: 17 – MWM/ZSM; 18 – ASV; 19 – SZMN (photo by V.V. Dubatolov)." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.3887626" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/3887626/files/figure.png" pageId="4" pageNumber="579">Figs 17–19</figureCitation>
) and 
<taxonomicName box="[1270,1437,1298,1325]" class="Insecta" family="Arctiidae" genus="Ghoria" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Lepidoptera" pageId="4" pageNumber="579" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="sinotibetica">
<emphasis box="[1270,1437,1298,1325]" italics="true" pageId="4" pageNumber="579">G. sinotibetica</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
(
<figureCitation box="[159,287,1333,1360]" captionStart="FIGURES 24–27" captionStartId="9.[151,264,1765,1790]" captionTargetBox="[183,1407,191,1734]" captionTargetId="figure@9.[176,1411,181,1740]" captionTargetPageId="9" captionText="FIGURES 24–27. Ghoria spp., male genitalia. Depositories of specimens: 24, 25, 27 – MWM/ZSM; 26 – SZMN (photo by V.V. Dubatolov)." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.3887630" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/3887630/files/figure.png" pageId="4" pageNumber="579">Figs 24–26</figureCitation>
) due to the relatively narrow valva. However, differs clearly from other relatives by the conspicuously elongated aedeagus vesica. In addition, compared to that of 
<taxonomicName box="[820,985,1368,1394]" class="Insecta" family="Arctiidae" genus="Ghoria" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Lepidoptera" pageId="4" pageNumber="579" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="sinotibetica">
<emphasis box="[820,985,1368,1394]" italics="true" pageId="4" pageNumber="579">G. sinotibetica</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
, the aedeagus of 
<taxonomicName authority="Volynkin &amp; Saldaitis &amp; Černý, 2020" authorityName="Volynkin &amp; Saldaitis &amp; Černý" authorityYear="2020" box="[1180,1342,1368,1394]" class="Insecta" family="Arctiidae" genus="Ghoria" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Lepidoptera" pageId="4" pageNumber="579" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="longivesica" status="sp. n.">
<emphasis box="[1180,1342,1368,1394]" italics="true" pageId="4" pageNumber="579">G. longivesica</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
<emphasis bold="true" box="[1348,1411,1368,1394]" pageId="4" pageNumber="579">
<taxonomicNameLabel box="[1348,1411,1368,1394]" pageId="4" pageNumber="579" rank="species">sp. n.</taxonomicNameLabel>
</emphasis>
is significantly broader and more elongated. The subbasal diverticulum of the new species is larger than that of 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Dubatolov, Kishida &amp; Wang" authorityYear="2012" class="Insecta" family="Arctiidae" genus="Ghoria" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Lepidoptera" pageId="4" pageNumber="579" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="nanlingica">
<emphasis italics="true" pageId="4" pageNumber="579">G. nanlingica</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
and 
<taxonomicName box="[284,450,1437,1463]" class="Insecta" family="Arctiidae" genus="Ghoria" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Lepidoptera" pageId="4" pageNumber="579" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="sinotibetica">
<emphasis box="[284,450,1437,1463]" italics="true" pageId="4" pageNumber="579">G. sinotibetica</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
, the subbasal chamber of vesica is less prominent than that of 
<taxonomicName box="[1156,1322,1437,1463]" class="Insecta" family="Arctiidae" genus="Ghoria" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Lepidoptera" pageId="4" pageNumber="579" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="sinotibetica">
<emphasis box="[1156,1322,1437,1463]" italics="true" pageId="4" pageNumber="579">G. sinotibetica</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
and bears much smaller spines than that of 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Dubatolov, Kishida &amp; Wang" authorityYear="2012" box="[525,680,1472,1498]" class="Insecta" family="Arctiidae" genus="Ghoria" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Lepidoptera" pageId="4" pageNumber="579" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="nanlingica">
<emphasis box="[525,680,1472,1498]" italics="true" pageId="4" pageNumber="579">G. nanlingica</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
. The female genitalia of 
<taxonomicName authority="Volynkin &amp; Saldaitis &amp; Černý, 2020" authorityName="Volynkin &amp; Saldaitis &amp; Černý" authorityYear="2020" box="[965,1127,1472,1498]" class="Insecta" family="Arctiidae" genus="Ghoria" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Lepidoptera" pageId="4" pageNumber="579" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="longivesica" status="sp. n.">
<emphasis box="[965,1127,1472,1498]" italics="true" pageId="4" pageNumber="579">G. longivesica</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
<emphasis bold="true" box="[1135,1199,1472,1498]" pageId="4" pageNumber="579">
<taxonomicNameLabel box="[1135,1199,1472,1498]" pageId="4" pageNumber="579" rank="species">sp. n.</taxonomicNameLabel>
</emphasis>
(
<figureCitation box="[1214,1296,1471,1498]" captionStart="FIGURES 32–36" captionStartId="11.[151,264,1829,1854]" captionTargetBox="[151,1431,182,1799]" captionTargetId="figure@11.[151,1435,181,1803]" captionTargetPageId="11" captionText="FIGURES 32–36. Ghoria spp., female genitalia. Specimens are deposited in MWM/ZSM." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.3887634" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/3887634/files/figure.png" pageId="4" pageNumber="579">Fig. 34</figureCitation>
) differ from those of other members of the species-group by the narrow, elliptical corpus bursae (that is sack-like or globular in other species) with a narrower area of spinulose scobination.
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
